# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: piston
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:piston/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Air-cooled engines are widely seen in applications where weight or simplicity is the primary goal.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity makes them suited for uses in small applications like chainsaws and lawn mowers, as well as small generators and similar roles.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] These qualities also make them highly suitable for aviation use, where they are widely used in general aviation aircraft and as auxiliary power units on larger aircraft.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity, in particular, also makes them common on motorcycles.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Most modern internal combustion engines are cooled by a closed circuit carrying liquid coolant through channels in the engine block and cylinder head.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] A fluid in these channels absorbs heat and then flows to a heat exchanger or radiator where the coolant releases heat into the air (or raw water, in the case of marine engines).
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Thus, while they are not *ultimately* cooled by the liquid, as the heat is exchanged with some other fluid like air, because of the liquid-coolant circuit they are known as *liquid-cooled*.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] In contrast, heat generated by an air-cooled engine is released directly into the air.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Typically this is facilitated with metal fins covering the outside of the cylinder head and cylinders which increase the surface area that air can act on.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Air may be force fed with the use of a fan and shroud to achieve efficient cooling with high volumes of air or simply by natural air flow with well designed and angled fins.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] In all combustion engines, a great percentage of the heat generated, around 44%, escapes through the exhaust.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Another 8% or so ends up in the oil, which itself has to be cooled in an oil cooler.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] This means less than half of the heat has to be removed through other systems.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] In an air-cooled engine, only about 12% of the heat flows out through the metal fins.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Air cooled engines usually run noisier, however it provides more simplicity which gives benefits when it comes to servicing and part replacement and is usually cheaper to be maintained.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Many motorcycles use air cooling for the sake of reducing weight and complexity.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Few current production automobiles have air-cooled engines (such as Tatra 815), but historically it was common for many high-volume vehicles.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] The orientation of the engine cylinders is commonly found in either single-cylinder or coupled in groups of two, and cylinders are commonly oriented in a horizontal fashion as a flat engine, while vertical straight-four engine have been used.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] During the 1920s and 30s there was a great debate in the aviation industry about the merits of air-cooled vs. liquid-cooled designs.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] At the beginning of this period, the liquid used for cooling was water at ambient pressure.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] The amount of heat carried away by a fluid is a function of its capacity and the difference in input and output temperatures.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] As the boiling point of water is reduced with lower pressure, and the water could not be efficiently pumped as steam, radiators had to have enough cooling power to account for the loss in cooling power as the aircraft climbed.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] The resulting radiators were quite large and caused a significant amount of aerodynamic drag.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] This placed the two designs roughly equal in terms of power to drag, but the air-cooled designs were almost always lighter and simpler.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] In 1921, the US Navy, largely due to the efforts of Commander Bruce G.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Leighton, decided that the simplicity of the air-cooled design would result in less maintenance workload, which was paramount given the limited working area of aircraft carriers.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Leighton's efforts led to the Navy underwriting air-cooled engine development at Pratt & Whitney and Wright Aeronautical.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Most other groups, especially in Europe where aircraft performance was rapidly improving, were more concerned with the issue of drag.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] While air-cooled designs were common on light aircraft and trainers, as well as some transport aircraft and bombers, liquid-cooled designs remained much more common for fighters and high-performance bombers.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] The drag issue was upset by the 1929 introduction of the NACA cowl, which greatly reduced the drag of air-cooled engines in spite of their larger frontal area, and the drag related to cooling was at this point largely even.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] This also led to development work attempting to eliminate the radiator entirely using evaporative cooling, allowing it to turn to steam and running the steam through tubes located just under the skin of the wings and fuselage, where the fast moving outside air condensed it back to water.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] While this concept was used on a number of record-setting aircraft in the late 1930s, it always proved impractical for production aircraft for a wide variety of reasons.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] In 1929, Curtiss began experiments replacing water with ethylene glycol in a Curtiss D-12 engine.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Ethylene glycol could run up to 250°C and reduced the radiator size by 50% compared to water-cooled designs.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] The experiments were extremely successful and by 1932 the company had switched all future designs to this coolant.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] At the time, Union Carbide held a monopoly on the industrial process to make ethylene glycol, so it was initially used only in the US, with Allison Engines picking it up soon after.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] It was not until the mid-1930s that Rolls-Royce adopted it as supplies improved, converting all of their engines to ethylene glycol.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] With the much smaller radiators and less fluid in the system, the weight and drag of these designs was well below contemporary air-cooled designs.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] On a weight basis, these liquid-cooled designs offered as much as 30% better performance.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] In the late- and post-war era, the high-performance field quickly moved to jet engines.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] This took away the primary market for late-model liquid-cooled engines.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Those roles that remained with piston power were mostly slower designs and civilian aircraft.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] In these roles, the simplicity and reduction in servicing needs is far more important than drag, and from the end of the war on almost all piston aviation engines have been air-cooled, with few exceptions.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] As of 2020, most of the engines manufactured by Lycoming and Continental are used by major manufacturers of light aircraft Cirrus, Cessna and so on.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Other engine manufactures using air-cooled engine technology are ULPower and Jabiru, more active in the Light-Sport Aircraft (LSA) and ultralight aircraft market.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Rotax uses a combination of air-cooled cylinders and liquid-cooled cylinder heads.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Some small diesel engines, e.g. those made by Deutz AG and Lister Petter are air-cooled.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Probably the only big Euro 5 truck air-cooled engine (V8 320 kW power 2100 N·m torque one) is being produced by Tatra.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] BOMAG part of the FAYAT group also utilizes an air cooled inline 6 cylinder motor, in many of their construction vehicles.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Stationary or portable engines were commercially introduced early in the 1900s.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] The first commercial production was by the New Way Motor Company of Lansing, Michigan, US.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] The company produced air-cooled engines in single and twin cylinders in both horizontal and vertical cylinder format.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Subsequent to their initial production which was exported worldwide, other companies took up the advantages of this cooling method, especially in small portable engines.
[src:piston/air-cooled-engine] Applications include mowers, generators, outboard motors, pump sets, saw benches and auxiliary power plants and more.
[src:piston/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:piston/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:piston/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:piston/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:piston/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:piston/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:piston/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:piston/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:piston/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:piston/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:piston/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:piston/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:piston/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:piston/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:piston/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:piston/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:piston/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:piston/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:piston/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:piston/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:piston/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:piston/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:piston/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:piston/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:piston/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:piston/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:piston/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:piston/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:piston/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:piston/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:piston/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:piston/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:piston/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:piston/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:piston/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:piston/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:piston/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:piston/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:piston/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:piston/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:piston/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:piston/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:piston/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:piston/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:piston/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:piston/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:piston/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:piston/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:piston/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:piston/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:piston/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:piston/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:piston/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:piston/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:piston/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:piston/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:piston/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:piston/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:piston/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:piston/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:piston/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:piston/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:piston/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:piston/air-gun] An **air gun** or **airgun** is a gun that uses compressed air or other pressurized gases to fire projectiles, reminiscent of the principle behind the ancient blowgun.
[src:piston/air-gun] This is in contrast to a firearm, which shoots projectiles using pressure generated via combustion of a chemical propellant, most often black powder in antique firearms and smokeless powder in modern firearms.
[src:piston/air-gun] Air guns come in both long gun (**air rifle**) and handgun (**air pistol**) forms.
[src:piston/air-gun] Both types typically propel metallic projectiles that are either diabolo-shaped pellets or spherical shots called BBs, although in recent years Minié ball-shaped cylindro-conoidal projectiles called slugs are becoming more popular.
[src:piston/air-gun] Certain types of air guns (usually air rifles) may also launch fin-stabilized projectile such as darts (e.g., tranquilizer guns) or hollow-shafted arrows (so-called "airbows").
[src:piston/air-gun] The air guns were first developed in the 16th century, and have since been used in hunting, shooting sports, and even in warfare.
[src:piston/air-gun] There are three different power sources for modern air guns, depending on the design: spring-piston, pneumatic or bottled compressed gas (most commonly carbon dioxide and recently nitrogen).
[src:piston/air-gun] Air guns represent the oldest pneumatic technology.
[src:piston/air-gun] The oldest existing mechanical air gun dates back to about 1580, and is currently kept in the Livrustkammaren Museum in Stockholm.
[src:piston/air-gun] This is approximately what most historians recognize as the beginning of the modern air gun.
[src:piston/air-gun] Throughout 17th to 19th century, air guns in .30 to .51 calibers were used to hunt big game, deer and wild boar.
[src:piston/air-gun] These air rifles were charged using a pump to fill an air reservoir and produced velocities from 650 to 1,000 ft/s (200 to 300 m/s).
[src:piston/air-gun] They were also used in warfare, the most recognized example being the Girandoni air rifle, a repeating rifle used by Austria in the 1788 war against Turkey.
[src:piston/air-gun] At that time, they had compelling advantages over the muzzleloader firearms of the day.
[src:piston/air-gun] For example, air guns could be discharged in wet weather and rain (unlike both matchlock and flintlock muskets), and discharged much faster than muzzle-loading guns.
[src:piston/air-gun] Moreover, they were quieter than a firearm of a similar caliber and produced no muzzle flash or smoke cloud when fired.
[src:piston/air-gun] Thus, they did not give away the shooter's position or obscure the shooter's view, unlike the black powder muskets of the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:piston/air-gun] In the hands of skilled soldiers, they gave the military a distinct advantage.
[src:piston/air-gun] France, Austria and other nations had special sniper detachments using air rifles, mostly Jäger (infantry).
[src:piston/air-gun] The Austrian 1779 model was named *Windbüchse* (literally "wind rifle" in German).
[src:piston/air-gun] The gun was developed in 1768 or 1769 by the Tyrolean Ladins watchmaker, mechanic and gunsmith Bartholomäus Girardoni (1744–1799) and is sometimes referred to as the Girandoni air rifle or Girardoni air gun in literature (the name is also spelled "Girandony", "Giradoni" or "Girardoni".).
[src:piston/air-gun] Adopted by the Austrian leadership in 1779, the *Windbüchse* was about 4 ft (1.2 m) long and weighed 10 pounds (4.5 kg), about the same size and mass as a conventional musket.
[src:piston/air-gun] The air reservoir was a removable, club-shaped, butt.
[src:piston/air-gun] The *Windbüchse* carried twenty-two .51 caliber (13 mm) lead balls in a tubular magazine.
[src:piston/air-gun] A skilled shooter could fire off one magazine in about thirty seconds.
[src:piston/air-gun] A shot from this air gun could penetrate a one-inch-thick (2.5 cm) wooden board at a hundred paces, an effect roughly equal to that of a modern 9×19mm or .45 ACP caliber pistol.
[src:piston/air-gun] Circa 1820, the Japanese inventor Kunitomo Ikkansai developed various manufacturing methods for guns, and also created an air gun based on the study of Western knowledge ("rangaku") acquired from the Dutch in Dejima.
[src:piston/air-gun] The Lewis and Clark Expedition (1804) carried a reservoir air gun, very likely the Girardoni, as it held 22 round balls of .46 caliber in a tubular magazine mounted on the side of the barrel.
[src:piston/air-gun] The butt of the gun served as the air reservoir and had a working pressure of 800 psi (55 bar).
[src:piston/air-gun] The rifle was said to be capable of 22 aimed shots per minute and had a rifled bore of 0.452 in (11.5 mm) and a groove diameter 0.462 in (11.7 mm).
[src:piston/air-gun] One of the first commercially successful and mass-produced air guns was manufactured by the William F.
[src:piston/air-gun] Markham's Markham Air Rifle Company in Plymouth, Michigan, US.
[src:piston/air-gun] Their first model air gun was the wooden *Challenger*, marketed in 1886.
[src:piston/air-gun] In response, Clarence Hamilton from the neighboring Plymouth Air Rifle Company (later renamed to Daisy Manufacturing Company in 1895) marketed their all-metal Daisy BB Gun in early 1888, which prompted Markham to respond with their *Chicago* model in 1888 followed by the *King* model in 1890.
[src:piston/air-gun] The *Chicago* model was sold by Sears, Roebuck for 73 cents in its catalog.
[src:piston/air-gun] In 1928, the name of the Markham company was changed to King Air Rifle Company after the company was purchased by Daisy in 1916 after decades of intense competition, and continued to manufacture the "King" model air rifle until 1935 before ceasing operation altogether in the 1940s.
[src:piston/air-gun] From the 1890s onwards, air rifles were used in Birmingham, England for competitive target shooting.
[src:piston/air-gun] Matches were held in public houses and working men's clubs, which sponsored shooting teams.
[src:piston/air-gun] This often took the form of Bell Target shooting, where the competitor aims to ring a bell by shooting through a small hole in a steel plate.
[src:piston/air-gun] Prizes, such as a leg of mutton for the winning team, were paid for by the losing team.
[src:piston/air-gun] During this time, over 4,000 air rifle clubs and associations existed across Great Britain, with as many as 1,600 in Birmingham alone.
[src:piston/air-gun] During this time, the air gun was associated with poaching because it could deliver a shot without a significant muzzle report.
[src:piston/air-gun] Air guns are used for hunting (small to medium game), pest control, recreational shooting (commonly known as plinking) and competitive sports such as the Olympic 10 m air rifle and 10 m air pistol events.
[src:piston/air-gun] Field target (FT) is a competitive form of metallic silhouette shooting in which the targets are animal-shaped steel targets with a "kill zone" cut-out.
[src:piston/air-gun] Hunter field target (HFT) is a variation, using identical equipment, but with differing rules.
[src:piston/air-gun] The distances FT and HFT competitions are shot at range between 7.3 and 41.1 metres (24 and 135 ft) for HFT & 7.3 and 50.29 metres (24.0 and 165.0 ft) for FT, with varying sizes of "reducers" being used to increase or decrease the size of the kill zone.
[src:piston/air-gun] In the UK, competition power limits are set at the legal maximum for an unlicensed air rifle, i.e.
[src:piston/air-gun] Air rifle benchrest is an international shooting sport where the objective is to hit a (small) bulls eye target at 25 m (27.34 yd) shooting distance.
[src:piston/air-gun] There are two divisions ARLV 12 ft⋅lbf (16.27 J) and ARHV 20 ft⋅lbf (27.12 J).
[src:piston/air-gun] The increasing affordability of higher-power pre-charged pneumatic (PCP) rifles has allowed large projectiles and further target distance for competition purposes.
[src:piston/air-gun] For instance, the Extreme Benchrest competition held annually in Green Valley, Arizona allows calibers up to .30 inches (7.6 mm) at 75 yd (68.58 m) while the Big Bore Benchrest arm of the same competition at other localities engages targets at 35 to 300 yards (32 to 274 m).
[src:piston/air-gun] The component of an airgun that provides the gas pressure needed to propel projectiles is called its *powerplant*, which uses internally stored pressurized gas; and *compressed gas* (most commonly CO2), which uses external sources of pressurized gas.
[src:piston/air-gun] A **spring-piston air gun** (also known as a **spring gun** or simply a "**springer**") operates by means of a spring-loaded piston pump assembly contained within a compression chamber separate from the gun barrel.
[src:piston/air-gun] Traditionally, a grease-lubricated steel coil spring is used as the powerplant main spring.
[src:piston/air-gun] Before shooting, the user needs to manually cock the gun by flexing a lever connected to the pump assembly, which pulls the pump piston rearwards and compresses the main spring until the rear of the piston engages the sear.
[src:piston/air-gun] When shooting, the trigger is pulled and disengages the sear, allowing the main spring to decompress and release its stored elastic potential energy, pushing the piston forward, thereby compressing the air in the pump cylinder.
[src:piston/air-gun] All this takes place in a fraction of a second, during which the air undergoes adiabatic heating to several hundred degrees and then cools as the air expands.
[src:piston/air-gun] This can also cause a phenomenon referred as "dieseling", where flammable substances in the compression chamber (e.g., petroleum-based lubricant) can be ignited by the compression heat like in a diesel engine, and lead to an afterburner effect with (often unpredictable) additional thrusts.
[src:piston/air-gun] This often results in combustion smoke coming out of the muzzle and potential pressure damage to the rubber O-ring seals inside the gun.
[src:piston/air-gun] Dieseling can be made to occur *intentionally* to increase power, by coating the pellet with lubricant or petroleum jelly, although this may result in damage to the breech seal.
[src:piston/air-gun] Most spring-piston guns are single-shot breechloaders by nature, but multiple-shot repeaters with magazine feeders have been introduced in recent years by manufacturers such as Gamo, Umarex and Hatsan.
[src:piston/air-gun] Spring-piston guns, especially the high-powered "magnum" guns, are able to achieve muzzle velocities exceeding the speed of sound.
[src:piston/air-gun] The effort required for the cocking stroke is proportional to the designed power of the gun, with higher muzzle velocities requiring a stiffer spring and hence a greater cocking effort.
[src:piston/air-gun] Spring-piston guns have a practical upper limit of 1,250 ft/s (380 m/s) for .177 cal (4.5 mm) pellets, as higher velocities cause unstable pellet flight and loss of accuracy.
[src:piston/air-gun] This is due to the extreme buffeting caused when the pellet reaches and surpasses transonic speed, then slows back down and goes through sound barrier again, which is more than enough to destabilize the pellet's flight.
[src:piston/air-gun] Shortly after leaving the barrel, the supersonic pellet falls back below the speed of sound and the shock wave overtakes the pellet, causing its flight stability to be disrupted.
[src:piston/air-gun] Drag increases disproportionately as pellet velocity increases, so it is generally better to increase pellet weight to keep velocities subsonic in high-powered guns.
[src:piston/air-gun] Many shooters find that velocities in the 800–900 ft/s (240–270 m/s) range offer an ideal balance between power and accuracy.
[src:piston/air-gun] Spring-piston guns, especially high-powered ("magnum") models, do still recoil as a result of the mainspring pushing the piston forward.
[src:piston/air-gun] Although the recoil is less than that of some cartridge firearms, it can make the gun difficult to shoot accurately as the spring recoil is in effect while the pellet is still within the barrel.
[src:piston/air-gun] Spring gun recoil also has a sharp forward component, caused by the piston hitting the front end of the pump chamber when the spring has fully decompressed.
[src:piston/air-gun] These rapid double-jerking movements are known to damage scopes not rated for spring gun usage.
[src:piston/air-gun] In addition, the spring often has unpredictable collateral transverse vibrations as well as torquing, both of which can cause accuracy to suffer.
[src:piston/air-gun] The better quality spring guns can have very long service lives, being simple to maintain and repair.
[src:piston/air-gun] Because they deliver the same mechanical energy output on each shot, external ballistics are quite consistent.
[src:piston/air-gun] Most Olympic air gun competitions through the 1970s and into the 1980s were shot with spring-piston guns, often of the opposing-piston recoil-eliminating type.
[src:piston/air-gun] Beginning in the 1980s, guns powered by compressed/liquefied carbon dioxide began to dominate the competition.
[src:piston/air-gun] Today, the guns used at the highest levels of competition are powered by compressed air.
[src:piston/air-gun] Some newer generation air guns incorporate a gas spring (commonly referred to as a *gas piston*, *gas ram*, *gas strut* or *nitro piston*) instead of a mechanical spring.
[src:piston/air-gun] The spring itself is essentially a stand-alone enclosed piston pump without outlets and with pressurized air or inert gas (such as nitrogen) held tightly sealed within the cylinder.
[src:piston/air-gun] When the gun is cocked, the gas inside the cylinder gets further compressed by the piston, stores potential energy and acts as a pneumatic accumulator.
[src:piston/air-gun] Gas spring units require higher precision to manufacture since they require a low-friction sliding seal that can withstand the high pressures within when cocked.
[src:piston/air-gun] Gas springs perform more reliably in cold climates than coil springs, because metallic coil springs need to be coated with lubricating grease which often thickens in low temperatures causing the gun to "freeze up".
[src:piston/air-gun] Gas springs also have less lateral and longitudinal vibrations than coil springs, hence are usually less "hold-sensitive", making it easier to achieve consistent shot groupings.
[src:piston/air-gun] Pneumatic airguns propel the projectiles by utilizing the pneumatic potential energy within compressed air, which is pressurized beforehand and stored inside the gun, and then released through valves during shooting.
[src:piston/air-gun] Single-stroke and multi-stroke pump guns utilize an on-board hand pump to pressurize air in an internal reservoir tank, while pre-charged pneumatic guns' reservoirs are filled from an external source using either a high-pressure stand pump or by decanting air from a larger diving cylinder.
[src:piston/air-gun] Because of the need for cylinders or charging systems, PCP guns have higher initial costs but much lower operating costs when compared to CO2 rifles, and have superior performance over ordinary pump guns.
[src:piston/air-gun] Having no significant movement of heavy mechanical parts during the discharge cycle, PCP airgun designs produce lower recoil, and can shoot as many as 100 shots per charge depending on the tank/reservoir size.
[src:piston/air-gun] The ready supply of air has allowed the development of semi- and fully automatic air guns.
[src:piston/air-gun] PCP guns are very popular in Europe because of their accuracy and ease of use.
[src:piston/air-gun] They are widely utilized in ISSF 10 meter air pistol and rifle shooting events and the sport of Field Target shooting, and are usually fitted with telescopic sights.
[src:piston/air-gun] Early stand pump designs encountered problems of fatigue (both human and mechanical), temperature warping, and condensation – none of which are beneficial to accurate shooting or the airguns' longevity.
[src:piston/air-gun] Modern stand pumps have multi-stage chambers and built-in air filtration systems and have overcome many of these problems.
[src:piston/air-gun] Using scuba-quality air decanted from a diving cylinder provides consistently clean, dry, high-pressure air.
[src:piston/air-gun] During the typical PCP's discharge cycle, the hammer of the rifle is released by the sear to strike the bash valve.
[src:piston/air-gun] The hammer may move rearwards or forwards, unlike firearms where the hammer almost always moves forward.
[src:piston/air-gun] The valve is held closed by a spring and the pressure of the air in the reservoir.
[src:piston/air-gun] The pressure of the spring is constant, and the pressure of the air released (which is also known as the *working pressure*) decreases with each successive shot.
[src:piston/air-gun] As a result, when the reservoir pressure is high, the valve opens less fully and closes faster than when the reservoir pressure is lower, resulting in a similar total volume of air flowing past the valve with each shot.
[src:piston/air-gun] This results in a degree of partial self-regulation that gives a greater consistency of velocity from shot to shot, which corresponds to the middle "plateau" phase of the gun's shot-to-shot muzzle velocity profile (also known as the *power curve* ).
[src:piston/air-gun] Well-designed PCP will display good shot-to-shot consistency over a long period, as the air reservoir is being depleted.
[src:piston/air-gun] Other PCP rifles and pistols are regulated, i.e. the firing valve operates within a secondary chamber separated from the main air reservoir by the regulator body.
[src:piston/air-gun] The regulator maintains the pressure within this secondary chamber at a set pressure (lower than the main reservoir's) until the main reservoir's pressure drops to the point where it can no longer do so.
[src:piston/air-gun] As a result, shot-to-shot consistency is maintained for longer than in an unregulated rifle, and the gun can also output more shots due to reduced waste of reservoir pressure.
[src:piston/air-gun] CO2 guns are popular for training, as the guns and ammunition are inexpensive, relatively safe to use, and no specialized facilities are needed for safety.
[src:piston/air-gun] In addition, they can be purchased and owned in areas where firearms possession is either strictly controlled or banned outright.
[src:piston/air-gun] Most CO2 powered guns are relatively inexpensive, and there are a few precision target guns available that use CO2.
[src:piston/air-gun] The high-pressure air (HPA) system, or *N2*, was originally developed for paintball markers as a replacement for CO2 cartridges, and uses powerlet interface-compatible diving cylinders filled with either pure nitrogen or compressed air (which is 78% nitrogen).
[src:piston/air-gun] Because nitrogen is more inert than CO2, it remains in the gaseous state longer when compressed; when it expands, it cools due to the Joule-Thomson effect, but at a far lower rate than liquid CO2 because there is no change in state from liquid to gas.
[src:piston/air-gun] This thermostability reduces the variation in output pressure associated with rapid successions of firing cycles, improving accuracy and reliability in extreme climates.
[src:piston/air-gun] However, because compressed air is stored at higher pressures (up to 34 MPa or 4,900 psi) than liquid CO2 (stored at around 8 MPa or 1,200 psi), HPA cylinders are more expensive.
[src:piston/air-gun] Cylinders smaller than 1.1 L (67 cu in) may not even last as long as a standard CO2 cartridge when subjected to frequent use.
[src:piston/air-gun] It is also possible to power an HPA-compatible gun directly from a plug-in air compressor without using a gas cylinder, though this type of setup is rare.
[src:piston/air-gun] Each air cartridge is essentially a self-contained gas reservoir housed inside a cartridge case (usually in the size of a .38 Special), with an internal bash valve designed to release the content when the base of the cartridge is struck.
[src:piston/air-gun] Prior to shooting, each cartridge is pre-filled with sufficient compressed air for one shot (typically via a multi-stroke hand pump) and has a .177/.22 caliber pellet pre-seated to its front slot, and the entire cartridge is then inserted into a chamber in the gun barrel.
[src:piston/air-gun] When shooting, the hammer hits the rear of the air cartridge, mimicking the function of a centerfire ammunition.
[src:piston/air-gun] This allows the airgun to be constructed and operated in similar fashions to genuine firearms.
[src:piston/air-gun] It also allows for higher shot consistency because each cartridge can be easily filled to an identical air charge, essentially removing the "power curve" of conventional PCP guns and bypassing any need for regulators.
[src:piston/air-gun] It also simplifies the magazine feed design and eliminates the risk of deforming the projectiles when the action seats each pellet, as the soft lead pellet is protected from contact with the action probe by the harder cartridge casing.
[src:piston/air-gun] The air cartridge system, both in the rifle and revolver forms, was at the peak of its popularity throughout the 1990s.
[src:piston/air-gun] The popularity of the Brocock range was such that, by 2002, estimates put the number of air cartridge guns in circulation around 70,000-80,000.
[src:piston/air-gun] However, a small number of incidents relating to the alleged illegal conversion of (mainly) Brococks to allow them to discharge live ammunition sparked a media frenzy.
[src:piston/air-gun] After the UK government implemented the Anti-social Behaviour Act 2003 in January 2004, it became illegal to possess such airguns without a firearm certificate in the United Kingdom.
[src:piston/air-gun] Brocock subsequently ceased production of all air cartridge systems and turned to focus primarily on PCP airguns.
[src:piston/air-gun] The most popular ammunition used in rifled air guns is made of lead, a heavy metal.
[src:piston/air-gun] Lead is highly poisonous (whether inhaled or swallowed), affecting almost every organ and system in the human body.
[src:piston/air-gun] For this reason, lead-free pellets are becoming increasingly popular, and are available in all major shapes and styles, just like traditional lead pellets.
[src:piston/air-gun] In flight, the skirt has greater drag-to-weight ratio than the head and exerts a rearward pull behind the center of mass, similar to that of a shuttlecock.
[src:piston/air-gun] This produces a phenomenon known as *drag stabilization*, which helps to counteract yawing and maintain a consistent flight path.
[src:piston/air-gun] However, the diabolo shape also means that the overall pellet will have poor ballistic coefficient and tends to lose energy quickly and be more unstable especially in the transonic region (272–408 m/s ~ 893–1340 ft/s).
[src:piston/air-gun] Diabolo pellets are conventionally made from lead, but are widely available in non-lead alternatives, such as tin, or a combination of materials such as steel or gold alloys with polymer tips.
[src:piston/air-gun] A variety of lead-free pellets are offered by all major pellet manufacturers, including H&N Sport, RWS, JSB, Gamo, and others.
[src:piston/air-gun] Since lead is very dense, it has a higher ballistic coefficient than lightweight alternatives such as tin, copper, or plastic.
[src:piston/air-gun] At the present time, the airgun industry does not mass-produce dense alternatives to lead with a high ballistic coefficient for long-range shooting.
[src:piston/air-gun] Some manufacturers also have recently introduced the more cylindro-conoidal-shaped "slug" pellets for the more powerful modern PCP air rifles.
[src:piston/air-gun] Appropriately sized bullets cast from firearm bullet molds can be used in big bore air rifles.
[src:piston/air-gun] Caution should be used when handling lead projectiles or preparing animals for food, as lead fragments can be easily missed inside the meat.
[src:piston/air-gun] Lead-free slugs in airgun calibers are gradually being developed and becoming available for purchase from manufacturers such as Zan Projectiles, due in part to regulations on hunting with lead projectiles in many areas.
[src:piston/air-gun] The BB shot was once the most common airgun ammunition in the US, thanks to the popularity of Daisy's line of BB airguns.
[src:piston/air-gun] A BB is a small metallic ball in 4.5 mm/.177" diameter, typically made of steel (with a copper or zinc coating) or lead.
[src:piston/air-gun] Originally called the "round shot", the contemporary name came from the "BB"- size lead birdshot used in shotgun shells, which the first BB gun invented in 1886 was designed to shoot.
[src:piston/air-gun] Steel BBs can be acceptably accurate at short distances when fired from properly designed BB guns with smoothbore barrels.
[src:piston/air-gun] Lead #3 buckshot pellets can be used in .25" caliber airguns as if they were large BBs.
[src:piston/air-gun] Therefore, steel BBs lack the spin stabilization required for long-range accuracy, and usage in any but the cheapest rifled guns is discouraged.
[src:piston/air-gun] The softer lead BBs, however, can be used in rifled barrels.
[src:piston/air-gun] Typically BBs are used for indoor practice, casual outdoor plinking, training children, or to save money, as they are significantly cheaper than pellets.
[src:piston/air-gun] Replica CO2 pistols allow people to train with a BB gun, saving a lot of money to centerfire firearm cartridges.
[src:piston/air-gun] Care should be exercised to avoid ricochet, and safety glasses are recommended.
[src:piston/air-gun] Recently, manufacturers have created frangible BBs, which break apart and do not ricochet, reducing the hazards associated with BB guns.
[src:piston/air-gun] Some shotgunners use sightless BB rifles to train in instinctive shooting.
[src:piston/air-gun] Similar guns were also used briefly by the United States Army in a Vietnam-era instinctive shooting program called "Quick Kill".
[src:piston/air-gun] In the 18th and 19th centuries, air gun darts were popular, largely because they could be reused.
[src:piston/air-gun] Although less popular now, several different types of darts are made to be used in air guns, but it is not recommended that darts be used in air guns with rifled bores or in spring-powered air guns.
[src:piston/air-gun] Air guns that shoot darts are sometimes called *dart guns*, and *tranquilizer guns* if the darts used are loaded with anesthetic (tranquilizer) compounds.
[src:piston/air-gun] Some modern air guns are designed to discharge arrows and are called *arrow guns* or sometimes *airbows*.
[src:piston/air-gun] These arrows are designed with a hollow shaft that is open in the rear where the nock would normally be.
[src:piston/air-gun] When loaded, the hollow arrow shaft is slid rearwards over a barrel whose external diameter is only fractionally smaller than the shaft's interior diameter, providing a close-enough fitting that minimizes rattling and gives a reasonable enveloping seal without causing too much friction.
[src:piston/air-gun] During shooting, the trigger releases high-pressure air from the barrel to the front portion of the hollow arrow shaft, pushing the arrow forward.
[src:piston/air-gun] Such air guns can shoot arrows at launch velocities rivalling or even exceeding high-end crossbows, while retaining consistency of precision unaffected by archer's paradox, but they are also more expensive to set up and maintain.
[src:piston/air-gun] The modern pentathlon has since 2009 included a laser-run event that replaced the traditional cross country run of 3,200 metres and timed air-pistol shoot.
[src:piston/air-gun] The competitors run 4 laps of 800 m combined with 4 rounds of firing.
[src:piston/air-gun] The pistols used are modified air pistols that fire an eye-safe laser beam towards a target at the same time as a discharge of air.
[src:piston/air-gun] This has made the organisation of the events easier from a safety point of view and allows competitors to travel more easily with their weapons.
[src:piston/air-gun] Airsoft pellets are plastic BBs shot from airsoft guns.
[src:piston/air-gun] Larger caliber air rifles suitable for hunting large animals are offered by major manufacturers.
[src:piston/air-gun] Custom air guns are available in even larger calibers such as 20 mm (0.79") or .87 (22.1 mm).
[src:piston/air-gun] While in some countries air guns are not subject to any specific regulation, in most, there are laws which differ widely.
[src:piston/air-gun] Each jurisdiction has its definition of an air gun.
[src:piston/air-gun] Regulations may vary for weapons of different bore, muzzle energy, velocity, or ammunition material.
[src:piston/air-gun] Guns designed to fire metal pellets are often more tightly controlled than airsoft weapons.
[src:piston/air-gun] There may be a minimum age for possession, and sales of both air guns and ammunition may be restricted.
[src:piston/air-gun] Some areas require permits and background checks similar to those required for propellant type firearms.
[src:piston/air-gun] While historical air guns have been made specifically for warfare, modern air guns can also be deadly.
[src:piston/air-gun] In medical literature, modern air guns have been noted as a cause of death.
[src:piston/air-gun] This has been the case for guns of caliber .177 and .22 that are within the legal muzzle energy of air guns in the United Kingdom.
[src:piston/air-gun] For reason of safety and security a rule of use of the safety flag has been strictly mentioned by ISSF for the 10m air pistol and rifle shooting sports events.
[src:piston/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:piston/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:piston/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:piston/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:piston/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:piston/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:piston/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:piston/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:piston/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:piston/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:piston/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:piston/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:piston/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:piston/piston] A **piston** is a component of reciprocating engines, reciprocating pumps, gas compressors, hydraulic cylinders and pneumatic cylinders, among other similar mechanisms.
[src:piston/piston] It is the moving component that is contained by a cylinder and is made gas-tight by piston rings.
[src:piston/piston] In an engine, its purpose is to transfer force from expanding gas in the cylinder to the crankshaft via a piston rod and/or connecting rod.
[src:piston/piston] In a pump, the function is reversed and force is transferred from the crankshaft to the piston for the purpose of compressing or ejecting the fluid in the cylinder.
[src:piston/piston] In some engines, the piston also acts as a valve by covering and uncovering ports in the cylinder.
[src:piston/piston] An internal combustion engine is acted upon by the pressure of the expanding combustion gases in the combustion chamber space at so the top of the cylinder.
[src:piston/piston] This force then acts downwards through the connecting rod and onto the crankshaft.
[src:piston/piston] The connecting rod is attached to the piston by a swivelling gudgeon pin (US: wrist pin).
[src:piston/piston] This pin is mounted within the piston: unlike the steam engine, there is no piston rod or crosshead (except big two stroke engines).
[src:piston/piston] The typical piston design is on the picture.
[src:piston/piston] This type of piston is widely used in car diesel engines.
[src:piston/piston] According to purpose, supercharging level and working conditions of engines the shape and proportions can be changed.
[src:piston/piston] High-power diesel engines work in difficult conditions.
[src:piston/piston] Maximum pressure in the combustion chamber can reach 20 MPa and the maximum temperature of some piston surfaces can exceed 450 °C.
[src:piston/piston] It is possible to improve piston cooling by creating a special cooling cavity.
[src:piston/piston] Injector supplies this cooling cavity «A» with oil through oil supply channel «B».
[src:piston/piston] For better temperature reduction construction should be carefully calculated and analysed.
[src:piston/piston] Oil flow in the cooling cavity should be not less than 80% of the oil flow through the injector.
[src:piston/piston] The pin itself is of hardened steel and is fixed in the piston, but free to move in the connecting rod.
[src:piston/piston] A few designs use a 'fully floating' design that is loose in both components.
[src:piston/piston] All pins must be prevented from moving sideways and the ends of the pin digging into the cylinder wall, usually by circlips.
[src:piston/piston] Gas sealing is achieved by the use of piston rings.
[src:piston/piston] These are a number of narrow iron rings, fitted loosely into grooves in the piston, just below the crown.
[src:piston/piston] The rings are split at a point in the rim, allowing them to press against the cylinder with a light spring pressure.
[src:piston/piston] Two types of ring are used: the upper rings have solid faces and provide gas sealing; lower rings have narrow edges and a U-shaped profile, to act as oil scrapers.
[src:piston/piston] There are many proprietary and detail design features associated with piston rings.
[src:piston/piston] Pistons are usually cast or forged from aluminium alloys.
[src:piston/piston] For better strength and fatigue life, some racing pistons may be forged instead.
[src:piston/piston] Billet pistons are also used in racing engines because they do not rely on the size and architecture of available forgings, allowing for last-minute design changes.
[src:piston/piston] Although not commonly visible to the naked eye, pistons themselves are designed with a certain level of ovality and profile taper, meaning they are not perfectly round, and their diameter is larger near the bottom of the skirt than at the crown.
[src:piston/piston] Early pistons were of cast iron, but there were obvious benefits for engine balancing if a lighter alloy could be used.
[src:piston/piston] To produce pistons that could survive engine combustion temperatures, it was necessary to develop new alloys such as Y alloy and Hiduminium, specifically for use as pistons.
[src:piston/piston] A few early gas engines had double-acting cylinders, but otherwise effectively all internal combustion engine pistons are single-acting.
[src:piston/piston] During World War II, the US submarine *Pompano* was fitted with a prototype of the infamously unreliable H.O.R. double-acting two-stroke diesel engine.
[src:piston/piston] Although compact, for use in a cramped submarine, this design of engine was not repeated.
[src:piston/piston] Trunk pistons are long relative to their diameter.
[src:piston/piston] They act both as a piston and cylindrical crosshead.
[src:piston/piston] As the connecting rod is angled for much of its rotation, there is also a side force that reacts along the side of the piston against the cylinder wall.
[src:piston/piston] Trunk pistons have been a common design of piston since the early days of the reciprocating internal combustion engine.
[src:piston/piston] They were used for both petrol and diesel engines, although high speed engines have now adopted the lighter weight slipper piston.
[src:piston/piston] A characteristic of most trunk pistons, particularly for diesel engines, is that they have a groove for an oil ring below the gudgeon pin, in addition to the rings between the gudgeon pin and crown.
[src:piston/piston] The name 'trunk piston' derives from the 'trunk engine', an early design of marine steam engine.
[src:piston/piston] To make these more compact, they avoided the steam engine's usual piston rod with separate crosshead and were instead the first engine design to place the gudgeon pin directly within the piston.
[src:piston/piston] Otherwise these trunk engine pistons bore little resemblance to the trunk piston; they were extremely large diameter and double-acting.
[src:piston/piston] Their 'trunk' was a narrow cylinder mounted in the centre of the piston.
[src:piston/piston] Large slow-speed Diesel engines may require additional support for the side forces on the piston.
[src:piston/piston] These engines typically use crosshead pistons.
[src:piston/piston] The main piston has a large piston rod extending downwards from the piston to what is effectively a second smaller-diameter piston.
[src:piston/piston] The main piston is responsible for gas sealing and carries the piston rings.
[src:piston/piston] The smaller piston is purely a mechanical guide.
[src:piston/piston] It runs within a small cylinder as a trunk guide and also carries the gudgeon pin.
[src:piston/piston] Lubrication of the crosshead has advantages over the trunk piston as its lubricating oil is not subject to the heat of combustion: the oil is not contaminated by combustion soot particles, it does not break down owing to the heat and a thinner, less viscous oil may be used.
[src:piston/piston] The friction of both piston and crosshead may be only half of that for a trunk piston.
[src:piston/piston] Because of the additional weight of these pistons, they are not used for high-speed engines.
[src:piston/piston] A **slipper piston** is a piston for a petrol engine that has been reduced in size and weight as much as possible.
[src:piston/piston] In the extreme case, they are reduced to the piston crown, support for the piston rings, and just enough of the piston skirt remaining to leave two lands so as to stop the piston rocking in the bore.
[src:piston/piston] The sides of the piston skirt around the gudgeon pin are reduced away from the cylinder wall.
[src:piston/piston] The purpose is mostly to reduce the reciprocating mass, thus making it easier to balance the engine and so permit high speeds.
[src:piston/piston] In racing applications, slipper piston skirts can be configured to yield extremely light weight while maintaining the rigidity and strength of a full skirt.
[src:piston/piston] Reduced inertia also improves mechanical efficiency of the engine: the forces required to accelerate and decelerate the reciprocating parts cause more piston friction with the cylinder wall than the fluid pressure on the piston head.
[src:piston/piston] A secondary benefit may be some reduction in friction with the cylinder wall, since the area of the skirt, which slides up and down in the cylinder is reduced by half.
[src:piston/piston] However, most friction is due to the piston rings, which are the parts which actually fit the tightest in the bore and the bearing surfaces of the wrist pin, and thus the benefit is reduced.
[src:piston/piston] Deflector pistons are used in two-stroke engines with crankcase compression, where the gas flow within the cylinder must be carefully directed in order to provide efficient scavenging.
[src:piston/piston] With cross scavenging, the transfer (inlet to the cylinder) and exhaust ports are on directly facing sides of the cylinder wall.
[src:piston/piston] To prevent the incoming mixture passing straight across from one port to the other, the piston has a raised rib on its crown.
[src:piston/piston] This is intended to deflect the incoming mixture upwards, around the combustion chamber.
[src:piston/piston] Much effort, and many different designs of piston crown, went into developing improved scavenging.
[src:piston/piston] The crowns developed from a simple rib to a large asymmetric bulge, usually with a steep face on the inlet side and a gentle curve on the exhaust.
[src:piston/piston] Despite this, cross scavenging was never as effective as hoped.
[src:piston/piston] Most engines today use Schnuerle porting instead.
[src:piston/piston] This places a pair of transfer ports in the sides of the cylinder and encourages gas flow to rotate around a vertical axis, rather than a horizontal axis.
[src:piston/piston] In racing engines, piston strength and stiffness is typically much higher than that of a passenger car engine, while the weight is much less, to achieve the high engine RPM necessary in racing.
[src:piston/piston] Hydraulic cylinders can be both single-acting or double-acting.
[src:piston/piston] A hydraulic actuator controls the movement of the piston back and/or forth.
[src:piston/piston] Guide rings guides the piston and rod and absorb the radial forces that act perpendicularly to the cylinder and prevent contact between sliding the metal parts.
[src:piston/piston] Steam engines are usually double-acting (i.e. steam pressure acts alternately on each side of the piston) and the admission and release of steam is controlled by slide valves, piston valves or poppet valves.
[src:piston/piston] Consequently, steam engine pistons are nearly always comparatively thin discs: their diameter is several times their thickness.
[src:piston/piston] Piston pumps can be used to move liquids or compress gases.
[src:piston/piston] There are two special type of pistons used in air cannons: close tolerance pistons and double pistons.
[src:piston/piston] In close tolerance pistons O-rings serve as a valve, but O-rings are not used in double piston types.
